POD1000000014_S0000006	peter tyndall is a big beast of the ombudsman world he's a dubliner
POD1000000014_S0000007	he's now ombudsman for ireland having recently been reappointed to serve a second term
POD1000000014_S0000008	he has a long association with wales where he occupied a variety of senior positions in housing and social care
POD1000000014_S0000009	he then became public service ombudsman for wales between two thousand eight and thirteen
POD1000000014_S0000010	he's been chairman of the british and irish ombudsman association for two years and currently he's the president of the world board of the international ombudsman institute for the last four years
POD1000000014_S0000011	peter you're extremely welcome thank you for being with us
POD1000000014_S0000012	thank you rob very glad to be here
POD1000000014_S0000013	peter um i'm very interested to hear a bit about your early life
POD1000000014_S0000014	where were you born and tell us a bit about the values that were instilled in you when you grew up
POD1000000014_S0000015	um thank you rob i was born in dublin i was born into a fairly ordinary working-class home
POD1000000014_S0000016	my dad was a um mechanic with the state transport company my mother was um as was the case with many in the day a housewife
POD1000000014_S0000017	we lived a very ordinary family life
POD1000000014_S0000018	i didn't enjoy school and i was taught by the christian brothers so i have some of my learning to thank them for
POD1000000014_S0000019	was ah i wouldn't say they contributed to a a very happy schooldays but the rest of my childhood was very enjoyable so
POD1000000014_S0000020	my mother would have been quite religious it was a very different ireland at the time
POD1000000014_S0000021	our house was busy there were often relatives or neighbours popping in for cups of tea
POD1000000014_S0000022	and so was a a pleasant place to grow up
POD1000000014_S0000023	so you had a community service background before going to work in local government is that's that's correct isn't it
POD1000000014_S0000024	yes so i i worked for the welsh housing agency when it was set up that was funding housing associations on special needs housing
POD1000000014_S0000025	but then i went to work for cardiff housing department
POD1000000014_S0000026	i was responsible for services like homelessness and sheltered housing for older people and so on
POD1000000014_S0000027	and also managed the gypsy sites in cardiff so very interesting job
POD1000000014_S0000028	but i gradually became more involved in mainstream housing through that
POD1000000014_S0000029	and then before you became welsh ombudsman you were you were chief executive of the arts council of wales was was that good fun
POD1000000014_S0000030	it was very good fun it was at a time shortly after the creation of the welsh assembly
POD1000000014_S0000031	the government in wales was interested in nation-building if you like doing things to bring people together and they saw the arts as a valuable way of doing that
POD1000000014_S0000032	from my perspective obviously i was also interested in community arts and arts outreach to people who were otherwise excluded
POD1000000014_S0000033	so it fitted very well for me i i never had any expertise in the arts but i greatly enjoyed it
POD1000000014_S0000034	and it was a very good time for the arts in wales
POD1000000014_S0000035	now i think you must be one of the very few people to have occupied national ombudsman jobs in more than one country
POD1000000014_S0000036	i don't know whether there's anyone else like you in that regard but what was it like moving from being ombudsman in wales to ombudsman in in ireland
POD1000000014_S0000037	it was interesting
POD1000000014_S0000038	i think the ombudsman in wales was a very significant player in the evolution of the devolved administration in wales
POD1000000014_S0000039	um but particularly the work focused within the health sphere
POD1000000014_S0000040	and an awful lot of the complaints that we dealt with were to do with clinical judgement
POD1000000014_S0000041	so moving to ireland and firstly i found that i don't have jurisdiction over clinical judgement
POD1000000014_S0000042	but also i have jurisdiction over a much broader range of government services and local government
POD1000000014_S0000043	so was similar in some ways to wales but it was a a bigger job if you like
POD1000000014_S0000044	in the context of the a um whole national government and a different set of issues to deal with
POD1000000014_S0000045	in ireland you're also you wear many hats you're also the information commissioner
POD1000000014_S0000046	and you deal with local government ah standards as well
POD1000000014_S0000047	is is that do you find that an advantage in terms of being ombudsman
POD1000000014_S0000048	it's very helpful if you're committed to the same kinds of principles you're committed to good public services you're committed to openness you're committed to transparency
POD1000000014_S0000049	those values work across all of the different hats i wear
POD1000000014_S0000050	i suppose the biggest difference is as ombudsman you make recommendations but in ireland in the history of the office they've always been implemented
POD1000000014_S0000051	as information commissioner you make binding decisions but those get challenged in the courts
POD1000000014_S0000052	so despite what many people think to be the case being an ombudsman in some ways is more effective in terms of having outcomes achieved than having binding powers as information commissioner
POD1000000014_S0000053	what would you say have been the biggest challenges to you as irish ombudsman
POD1000000014_S0000054	you've obviously successfully dealt with them because you've been reappointed for a second term but looking back on the six years that you've had what what are the biggest challenges
POD1000000014_S0000055	the biggest challenge we faced was with the investigation into the magdalene laundries
POD1000000014_S0000056	as we looked more closely at the issues there this was about women who had been held against their will
POD1000000014_S0000057	often young women who'd had babies sometimes schoolchildren who'd been held against their will and forced to work for many years in laundries
POD1000000014_S0000058	what i was looking at was a government compensation scheme and the department of justice had chosen to interpret that scheme very narrowly
POD1000000014_S0000059	so they were excluding young women people who at the time were young women and had worked in the laundries but been detained in industrial schools
POD1000000014_S0000060	which shared the same sites as the laundries but not technically resident in the laundries
POD1000000014_S0000061	so we looked at that and felt that there was a huge injustice but the initial response of the department was to reject our findings
POD1000000014_S0000062	so that required a high-publicity campaign which ultimately led to the government changing its mind
POD1000000014_S0000063	to be fair i suspect if ministers had been involved from the outset i don't think that the rejection we initially saw would have happened
POD1000000014_S0000064	did any of the people who um experienced this detriment get in touch with you or was this the nature of you seeing the unfairness and acting on their behalf
POD1000000014_S0000065	no we had a small number of cases but we investigated the whole scheme and so some of the people who benefited wouldn't even have known of my office
POD1000000014_S0000066	so that's the advantage of having the power of own initiative to an ombudsman
POD1000000014_S0000067	ah yes it is you can investigate
POD1000000014_S0000068	even if you get complaints sometimes you're constrained because you can only investigate on the facts if you can't undertake own-initiative investigations
POD1000000014_S0000069	if something comes up that needs to be looked at there's no constraints on me looking at that
POD1000000014_S0000070	and particularly i've found that ah in the context of excluded groups it's a very powerful tool to use to make sure that people who don't come to you can nonetheless have access to justice
POD1000000014_S0000071	yeah and is that regarded as controversial in ireland i wouldn't have thought so
POD1000000014_S0000072	no no it's just part of the ah toolkit available to the office i don't think anybody gives it any second thought
POD1000000014_S0000073	and you you behaved very bravely in in this investigation because at one point when you were being blocked by ministers you threatened to go to the
POD1000000014_S0000075	is that is that right
POD1000000014_S0000076	when i was being blocked by officials i went to the minister for justice and through him to the
POD1000000014_S0000078	the prime minister
POD1000000014_S0000079	i asked that they personally look to resolve the matter because it was such a a stark injustice some reflected very poorly on the government of ireland
POD1000000014_S0000081	gone the minister for justice both acted with great expediency and the matter was resolved almost immediately following their intervention
POD1000000014_S0000082	i don't think you can be an effective ombudsman without having the kind of guts that you've shown throughout this
POD1000000014_S0000083	and the i hope you will sympathise with those ombudsmen that don't have own-initiative powers because it seems to me to be a great hand
POD1000000014_S0000084	i don't think it is i mean even in a welsh context where i didn't have them at the time
POD1000000014_S0000085	you could be investigating something in one health board and see immediately that it was likely that the same problems were arising elsewhere
POD1000000014_S0000086	but technically you couldn't extend your investigation beyond the body you were investigating
POD1000000014_S0000087	that ability to extend an investigation to cover whichever bodies are involved is very powerful
POD1000000014_S0000088	so a lot of my work let's say with asylum seekers and refugees in accommodation provided on behalf of the government
POD1000000014_S0000089	and i will be looking at complaints that are to do with healthcare that are to do with access to benefits that are to do with all kinds of things access to housing
POD1000000014_S0000090	other than the services provided by the department of justice in providing the accommodation
POD1000000014_S0000091	so it is just that capacity to broaden out an investigation as well as the capacity to instigate an investigation where you don't have complaints
POD1000000014_S0000092	now my current own-initiative investigation is looking at the situation of people under sixty-five living in nursing homes
POD1000000014_S0000093	that's become a much more pressing issue and the coronavirus crisis one of the people we've interviewed has already died another has contracted the virus
POD1000000014_S0000094	so although at this point it's not possible for obvious reasons to conclude the investigation
POD1000000014_S0000095	what we have done is written to the leaders of all the political parties who are currently involved and talks leading to the formation of a new government
POD1000000014_S0000096	to highlight the issue of people in institutional care so that at least what we've learnt to date in the course of our investigation can hopefully help to shape the policies of the incoming government
POD1000000014_S0000097	can we just move on a little bit
POD1000000014_S0000098	you you are the president of the international ombudsman institute which is a very important and prestigious job which is very valuable to ombudsmen all over the world
POD1000000014_S0000099	what added value do you think the i o i brings to to our discussions
POD1000000014_S0000100	well i think one the very important things is straightforwardly learning from each other
POD1000000014_S0000101	being an ombudsman is necessarily an isolated role what you can't do is be too close to the people in the services which are within your jurisdiction
POD1000000014_S0000102	so consequently we have more in common with each other than we do with the people whose services we're looking at and learning from each other is very important
POD1000000014_S0000103	the i o i provides structured training opportunities that's been one of the the very valuable things we've done
POD1000000014_S0000104	it provides best practice papers to show how things can best be done
POD1000000014_S0000105	and of course rob you yourself have been responsible for the best practice paper on on peer review and the work you've done in that field
POD1000000014_S0000106	and but also i think the i o i has played a big part in supporting ombudsman organisations under threat
POD1000000014_S0000107	we've seen for instance colleagues in many countries around the world who because they're doing their job are being threatened or ignored by their governments
POD1000000014_S0000108	and we've seen things like budgets being cut and we've seen people being denounced by government ministers and so on
POD1000000014_S0000109	so the solidarity of the international ombudsman community is very important but we also intervene quite directly
POD1000000014_S0000110	i give an example of um cyprus where the auditor-general was looking to interfere in the work of the ombudsman's office
POD1000000014_S0000111	following intervention from the i o i and others with the government of cyprus and the parliament in particular the threats were withdrawn
POD1000000014_S0000112	and in poland the ombudsman was threatened with large cuts to his budget we sent in a commission of inquiry
POD1000000014_S0000113	we interviewed government ministers we interviewed the judiciary
POD1000000014_S0000114	and we carried out press conferences we talked to n g os and we managed to get a stay of execution
POD1000000014_S0000115	and so we saw major threats to democracy there but our intervention along with those of others has helped to ensure that that office is still there and is continuing to operate effectively
POD1000000014_S0000116	that polish intervention was crucial
POD1000000014_S0000117	and what's one of the remarkable things about it was you actually went there didn't just talk about it
POD1000000014_S0000118	but you put the political institutions under pressure by asking them to give an account of what they were doing
POD1000000014_S0000119	absolutely so we did that in person and we did it through the media so that it had a very high profile within poland i think it's ah it's no good
POD1000000014_S0000120	i did the same in cyprus media interviews and talk to people on the ground
POD1000000014_S0000121	i think it's really important that solidarity is not something that comes just in the form of the letter though sometimes a letter can be effective enough in itself
POD1000000014_S0000122	but that you actually scale the intervention to the nature of the challenge
POD1000000014_S0000123	we we've talked about this quite a lot when we've not been on the radio but
POD1000000014_S0000124	how important do you think it is that we as ombuds do not get involved in political matters
POD1000000014_S0000125	or do you think this is a cultural relic of british imperialism
POD1000000014_S0000127	whatever about british imperialism no i think it's a very complex question
POD1000000014_S0000128	i think that for an ombudsman not to be involved in politics is scarcely possible because what we're actually doing is overseeing the services provided by the state
POD1000000014_S0000129	and so therefore any comment we make on those services has the potential to be political
POD1000000014_S0000130	what we can't be is party political and what we can't do is speak beyond the evidence of our casebook
POD1000000014_S0000131	so i talked earlier on about seeking to um effect the formation of the government in ireland to to promote particular policies to favour disadvantaged groups of people
POD1000000014_S0000132	but i'm doing that on the basis of investigations i'm carrying out
POD1000000014_S0000133	i'm not doing it as peter tyndall citizen i'm doing it as ombudsman of ireland based on the evidence from my casebook
POD1000000014_S0000134	and under those circumstances i think it's entirely appropriate to intervene
POD1000000014_S0000135	i think it becomes problematic if people are seen to be intervening on issues which go beyond their own work as ombudsman
POD1000000014_S0000136	i think that's where it would become problematic
POD1000000014_S0000137	but i do think that if you've got evidence that it's important that you use that evidence where it can be most effective in securing justice for the people who've come to you
POD1000000014_S0000138	so we're moving towards the end but i wanted to ask you about how you're coping with the coronavirus
POD1000000014_S0000139	what sort of impact has it had short term and longer term on on the way you operate
POD1000000014_S0000140	yes it's an interesting one
POD1000000014_S0000141	um the the first thing was that we surprised ourselves by being able to get ourselves in a position to work remotely much quicker than we might have done otherwise
POD1000000014_S0000142	i suppose if it's proved anything it's that when there is a crisis it's surprising how long-term problems can be solved in a hurry
POD1000000014_S0000143	and so we've been able to operate all of our services more or less without change throughout the crisis
POD1000000014_S0000144	we've had some changes in volumes of work coming to us
POD1000000014_S0000145	we've put a bit more emphasis on project work but by and large people are able to make their complaints to us
POD1000000014_S0000146	they can ring us they can email us
POD1000000014_S0000147	they can ah contact us on the web
POD1000000014_S0000148	um we're even able to collect our post though we're discouraging people from using the post at the moment but the effect of that is that we can keep going
POD1000000014_S0000149	the difficulties we face are probably more to do with the difficulties being faced by the services we're dealing with
POD1000000014_S0000150	so we've told the health service we've told nursing homes and we've told the department of social protection which deals with benefits and pensions
POD1000000014_S0000151	that we understand that it will take them longer to respond to us and that in some instances they won't be able to
POD1000000014_S0000152	so so we understand that and but in general we've been able to keep going
POD1000000014_S0000153	just give an example of the kind of things we've been dealing with
POD1000000014_S0000154	we had one gentleman stuck in poland who couldn't get back to ireland who'd been denied benefit in ireland even though his wife and children were in ireland and he normally lived and worked
POD1000000014_S0000155	and we were able to intervene successfully so that he got his benefits so we're able to deal with issues as they arise
POD1000000014_S0000156	i think in the longer term there'll be two things really one of them is just practical
POD1000000014_S0000157	we now know that it's possible for more of our people to work effectively from home and i can't see us going back to the situation before where only a very small number of people did that
POD1000000014_S0000158	i think more people will work from home as a consequence of what we've learnt during the crisis
POD1000000014_S0000159	but the second issue for me has been the appalling death toll among people in institutional care many of whom shouldn't be there
POD1000000014_S0000160	and i think we have to redouble our efforts in working on their behalf after the crisis to make sure that should there be a resurgence or should something else like this come along
POD1000000014_S0000161	that they're not as exposed and as vulnerable as they are at the moment
POD1000000014_S0000162	it it makes complete sense for the ombudsman to be looking at both health and social care matters
POD1000000014_S0000163	and not as in this country to have a separation where one ombudsman looks at social care and the other looks at health
POD1000000014_S0000164	i i'll just if i may rob just add something
POD1000000014_S0000165	one the things that's noticeably different between ireland and the u k and england in particular is that there is a single national ombudsman in ireland
POD1000000014_S0000166	so that issues of health and social care can both come into my jurisdiction
POD1000000014_S0000167	the reality is these these are complex interlinked issues
POD1000000014_S0000168	i'm trying to deal with them with two separate ombudsman offices it's complicated enough as it is
POD1000000014_S0000169	trying to do so in the context where you have m p filters
POD1000000014_S0000170	where you have different systems applying in different parts of the u k is impossibly difficult for yourselves
POD1000000014_S0000171	but you manage it very well along with the local government ombudsman
POD1000000014_S0000172	and i have to say you've managed in practice to overcome the difficulties but it's also an impossibly complex scenario for complainants
POD1000000014_S0000173	in ireland somebody wants to complain about public services they come to my office
POD1000000014_S0000174	in your case it's much more complicated
POD1000000014_S0000175	and i do hope that the proposals for ombudsman reform that we've seen in in the u k over recent years are not entirely lost
POD1000000014_S0000176	and that we do come to a much more satisfactory situation where there's a proper national ombudsman and where people can bring their complaints regardless of what particular public service they're complaining about
POD1000000014_S0000177	and i do hope that happens before i die which i'm increasingly becoming doubtful about but we'll we'll have to wait and see
POD1000000014_S0000178	peter you conducted the peer review of my organisation and then you appeared before the select committee in parliament
POD1000000014_S0000179	so that was not an expected development
POD1000000014_S0000180	ah what what was it like being being the peer reviewer who had to go before the u k parliament
POD1000000014_S0000181	it was an interesting experience robert
POD1000000014_S0000182	i think it would have been much more challenging if i hadn't been um quite so impressed by the quality of the service your office provides
POD1000000014_S0000183	it wasn't as though when we looked at the service we used a lot of objective criteria
POD1000000014_S0000184	and obviously ah with any office there is room for improvement but in general i was able to give reassurance to the committee as the quality of service that complainants were receiving
POD1000000014_S0000185	but also to highlight some of the deficiencies in powers and in jurisdiction that are causing you difficulties in practice
POD1000000014_S0000186	but then i suppose what i'd want to say i was very impressed by the quality of the people in your office
POD1000000014_S0000187	and it was a very good experience they were very open with us
POD1000000014_S0000188	we talked to your staff without talking to yourself to the managers so we were able for people to express a view as they so fit and i think people were very complementary
POD1000000014_S0000189	so i think as i say it was an an interesting experience
POD1000000014_S0000190	it's always challenging to go before parliamentary committees and the session was quite searching
POD1000000014_S0000191	i think the committee wanted to reassure itself that this wasn't some kind of hagiography
POD1000000014_S0000192	but we were satisfied in the end that we were able to say no we've looked in detail at this office
POD1000000014_S0000193	there are areas which can improve but by and large this is an improving service that's delivering good-quality ombudsman service to the people of england and to the u k
POD1000000014_S0000194	well i think the structural point is that thanks to the i o i this this whole system of peer review looks like it has legs for the wider ombudsman community
POD1000000014_S0000195	and it is an effective and inexpensive way of adding to scrutiny of ombudsman schemes so thank you for the role that you played in pioneering that
POD1000000014_S0000196	one thing beyond that too rob is that ah
POD1000000014_S0000197	since the review was undertaken the i o i along with other bodies have worked quite hard
POD1000000014_S0000198	what the venice commission and the council of europe in developing a set of overriding principles for ombudsman offices the venice principles as they've become known
POD1000000014_S0000199	and they've now been adopted by the council of europe
POD1000000014_S0000200	and that's the first time there's been a proper international standard against which ombuds offices can be judged
POD1000000014_S0000201	and so i'm keen to see them being used as they are being used now in the context of peer review
POD1000000014_S0000202	so that there is an objective set of internationally recognised standards against which you're measuring a particular ombudsman office
POD1000000014_S0000203	so i think that's again marks another step forward and one that i'm very pleased to have seen develop
POD1000000014_S0000204	i think when i undertook the peer review of the catalonian ombudsman with my belgian counterpart
POD1000000014_S0000205	we used those very same venice principles as the benchmark against which to judge the catalonian ombudsman
POD1000000014_S0000206	and it is very helpful to have that because it's without prejudice
POD1000000014_S0000207	it applies to everyone so i think it is an important development
POD1000000014_S0000208	so two final questions how have you peter tyndall reacted to working remotely being at home with your family
POD1000000014_S0000209	i've enjoyed it to be honest
POD1000000014_S0000210	it hasn't been too frustrating the technology can be an issue from time to time but it it hasn't been too difficult
POD1000000014_S0000211	it it's been less difficult than i would have expected
POD1000000014_S0000212	does time goes on i think the issue of visible leadership comes into it doesn't it
POD1000000014_S0000213	so you know you actually want to to be with your people again but but it works surprisingly well
POD1000000014_S0000214	and
POD1000000014_S0000215	as i say i think for the office itself i think we'll see more remote working in the future
POD1000000014_S0000216	thank you so lastly then it's what i always ask my guests
POD1000000014_S0000217	what advice would you give to young colleagues newly arriving as caseworkers in the embryonic ombudsman profession
POD1000000014_S0000218	for me there is um there is a couple of characteristics that have to be embodied by people working in the service or as an ombudsman
POD1000000014_S0000219	we have to be objective we have to be fair
POD1000000014_S0000220	we have to be even-handed so the first advice often is make sure you know the whole story before you reach your conclusion
POD1000000014_S0000221	but underpinning all of that i would say that if you haven't got a passionate commitment to justice then you're in the wrong job
POD1000000014_S0000222	because what this fundamentally is about is people who believe in fairness people who believe in justice and people who want to use their own efforts to make sure that nobody is denied access to justice
POD1000000014_S0000223	and that's what we're here for
POD1000000014_S0000224	thank you so much peter
POD1000000014_S0000225	your answers were stimulating and also inspirational
