POD1000000017_S0000001	from the new york times magazine i'm nikole hannah-jones this is sixteen nineteen
POD1000000017_S0000003	this week wesley morris on the birth of american music
POD1000000017_S0000005	so last fall i am at my friend's house we are making dinner i'm chopping vegetables and i asked my friend brett who was cooking with me can you put on some music
POD1000000017_S0000006	and he said what do you wanna listen to and i said have you ever heard of yacht rock and he said what i said yacht rock have you ever heard of this and he goes no i have not
POD1000000017_S0000007	so he finds the yacht rock station in pandora which i don't know why or how he's still a pandora guy with all due respect to pandora he is one and he finds the yacht rock station
POD1000000017_S0000009	at some point brett has to go run an errand i think i might have sent him on one i don't remember but he's gone so i'm alone just me with the vegetables and the yacht rock
POD1000000017_S0000011	it gives me plenty of time to really think about the songs i'm hearing
POD1000000017_S0000013	we're talking about music made between the years of i don't know i would say like nineteen seventy-five to about nineteen eighty-three things like
POD1000000017_S0000015	aces how long
POD1000000017_S0000017	seals and crofts to doing summer breeze i'm hearing things like
POD1000000017_S0000019	steal away by robbie dupree
POD1000000017_S0000021	and the doobie brothers what a fool believes
POD1000000017_S0000023	it is like our soft rock-est period in american popular music
POD1000000017_S0000025	the joke of yacht rock is that whoever invented it whoever's making a playlist out of these songs is basically saying that they're inconsequential and that what's in them doesn't matter
POD1000000017_S0000027	but what i know i'm hearing is something bigger and deeper than that
POD1000000017_S0000029	every song has something about it that is similar to the other songs
POD1000000017_S0000031	i'm hearing things like rosanna by toto
POD1000000017_S0000033	which seems perfectly banal has a really good beat sort of builds to its chorus
POD1000000017_S0000035	but then at the end
POD1000000017_S0000037	i'm hearing
POD1000000017_S0000039	the great doo-wop harmonies of the fifties and sixties
POD1000000017_S0000041	there is something jazz like in the syncopated music of something like steely dan
POD1000000017_S0000043	you can hear in somebody like michael mcdonald
POD1000000017_S0000045	that is like a gospel breakdown
POD1000000017_S0000047	what i'm hearing in all of these songs is basically blackness
POD1000000017_S0000049	and the song in which i am hearing it the deepest and strongest and most powerfully at least to me standing in that kitchen chopping those vegetables was when kenny loggins's this is it comes on
POD1000000017_S0000051	it's got a kind of loosely disco like rhythm to it there's a lot of percussion sort of going back and forth and around
POD1000000017_S0000053	sure kenny loggins is basically sing-whispering the verses in this song
POD1000000017_S0000055	doing this very light
POD1000000017_S0000056	cool
POD1000000017_S0000058	and then in the pre-chorus kenny loggins disappears and who shows up michael mcdonald
POD1000000017_S0000060	giving kenny loggins plenty of time to gather himself
POD1000000017_S0000062	when he sings the word miracle he doesn't sing miracle he goes miracle
POD1000000017_S0000064	like he is scraping the bottom of a pan to get all of the good bits off of it before you pour the gravy in
POD1000000017_S0000066	scraping the pan is the blackest thing you can do as a singer and here is kenny loggins as this white artist doing it
POD1000000017_S0000068	and then the gravy comes
POD1000000017_S0000070	he is like at the top of the church at this point
POD1000000017_S0000071	he has elevated himself to the rafters there's like no more he is like at the roof trying to clear a way to get to heaven but there's just church roof in the way
POD1000000017_S0000073	he's not the greatest singer but there's a kind of gumption and nerve to the singing of this song
POD1000000017_S0000075	that cannot be denied a tip of the hat to him
POD1000000017_S0000076	i just had to stand there and i just i i i actually cracked up i i just put down the knife and i cracked up and it felt so pleasurable and then i started thinking about all these other singers i love
POD1000000017_S0000078	i'm thinking about amy winehouse
POD1000000017_S0000080	i'm thinking about annie lennox
POD1000000017_S0000082	i'm thinking about george michael
POD1000000017_S0000084	i think about chris stapleton
POD1000000017_S0000085	you practices this kind of muscly blues that gets written off as country because he's a big white guy in a hat
POD1000000017_S0000087	and one of the many phases in which david bowie really wanted to make r and b and soul music
POD1000000017_S0000089	this is the sound not just of black america but the sound of america it is deeply american almost especially when it's sung by british people like david bowie and annie lennox and amy winehouse
POD1000000017_S0000090	and it fills me with pride like i know that there is something irresistible and ultimately inevitable about black music being a part of american popular music
POD1000000017_S0000091	but it also reminds me that there's a history to this a very painful history and in the most perversely ironic way it's this historical pain that is responsible for this music
POD1000000017_S0000093	some of the oldest recordings we have of black american music are from the nineteen thirties
POD1000000017_S0000094	and they're songs that would have been sung by americans born into slavery there's this one called old ship of zion
POD1000000017_S0000095	you can hear in it these four men their voices are moving in and out of each other
POD1000000017_S0000097	and it's beautiful and it's also sad you can feel that in your bones
POD1000000017_S0000098	and then there'll be music that was completely the opposite like old coon dog for instance
POD1000000017_S0000100	you can hear the playfulness in the song
POD1000000017_S0000102	and you've got this banjo this great african instrument that becomes the bedrock of american music in so many ways and that thing is dancing
POD1000000017_S0000103	and then you have someone like billy mccrea
POD1000000017_S0000104	and oh my god you can hear in his singing what we would now call something like the livelong day
POD1000000017_S0000106	years and years of hard work
POD1000000017_S0000107	and unimaginable sorrow
POD1000000017_S0000109	you can also hear in all of this music
POD1000000017_S0000111	this undeniable sound of hope
POD1000000017_S0000113	all of these melodies and cadences and emotions are things that wouldn't be passed down generation after generation it's what you would have heard on a plantation it's what you would have heard walking by a plantation
POD1000000017_S0000114	it's what you would have heard passing a black person doing his job entertaining himself doing the drudgery of work the way a guy named thomas dartmouth rice did sometime around the eighteen thirties
POD1000000017_S0000115	as the story goes t d rice a white man this anonymous nobody actor trying to make ends meet
POD1000000017_S0000116	one day he's touring with a troupe in cincinnati or maybe it was pittsburgh we don't really know but the myth basically goes t d rice happened upon an old black man cleaning a horse in a stable
POD1000000017_S0000117	the man was doing his job on property owned by a white man named crow
POD1000000017_S0000119	he heard the tune this old black man was singing he saw the way this man moved his body as he was cleaning this horse
POD1000000017_S0000120	now we don't know what tune this old man would've been singing
POD1000000017_S0000122	whatever rice hears coming out of this man's mouth is captivating to him and what he sees is an opportunity
POD1000000017_S0000124	because showbiz in the eighteen thirties looked like this
POD1000000017_S0000126	italian operas
POD1000000017_S0000128	british plays entertainment imported from europe all the people performing this stuff would have been white the audiences would have been white
POD1000000017_S0000129	after all it's eighteen thirty slavery is in full effect
POD1000000017_S0000131	and when it came to entertainment there was nothing new nothing truly american
POD1000000017_S0000133	and so when t d rice hears this black man singing this song and moving his body in this particular way ding a light bulb goes off
POD1000000017_S0000134	and he takes that light bulb and runs all the way to the theater he figures out a way to melt down some cork
POD1000000017_S0000135	let's it cool presumably takes a rag or maybe even his hand if it's cool enough
POD1000000017_S0000137	and then he paints his face black
POD1000000017_S0000139	he goes out on stage but instead of doing his regular act he's got this horse groomer's tune except now he's given the tune lyrics
POD1000000017_S0000140	come listen all you gals and boys i'm just from tuckahoe i'm going to sing a little song my name's jim crow
POD1000000017_S0000142	and the lyrics give the horse groomer a name and the name is jim crow
POD1000000017_S0000144	so the crowd goes crazy they go so bananas the man gets twenty encores
POD1000000017_S0000146	this is the first time a paying audience is basically electrified by a white man with a black face this is the night that jim crow was allegedly introduced to america this mascot of american racism
POD1000000017_S0000147	and this is what america really wanted which was its own original art form that is not an italian opera and isn't some british guy coming over and thespianing all over them
POD1000000017_S0000148	and here is thomas dartmouth rice giving it to them this is the night that american popular culture was born
POD1000000017_S0000150	oh boy i mean you know how it goes this sensational thing happens and then everybody wants to get on the bandwagon and do their own
POD1000000017_S0000151	so you have other minstrel acts who come along and try to do what thomas dartmouth rice is doing a song and a dance
POD1000000017_S0000152	and a black face on their white skin
POD1000000017_S0000154	and then from these solo acts you have basically bands forming
POD1000000017_S0000156	and the bands have all the instruments that you would have in a band that you'd recognize now there is a banjo and a fiddle and some tambourines and percussion in the form of bones which would come from a pig sometimes
POD1000000017_S0000157	that is the formation of what will become the minstrel troupe
POD1000000017_S0000159	and the place that minstrelsy took hold was in the north
POD1000000017_S0000160	places like philadelphia and new york and boston where you'd have these theaters dedicated to minstrel acts where minstrel acts would just move into a theater and do their act night after night after night after night after night
POD1000000017_S0000161	and a lot of these performers had never been meaningfully south to have a meaningful relationship with black people and so they just made stuff up based on what they thought black people were like
POD1000000017_S0000163	they were able to draw on things that were coming to america from other parts of europe like the polka
POD1000000017_S0000165	and so you would had over the course of the formation of this culture an inherent mixing you had some amazing mix of an imagined blackness
POD1000000017_S0000166	real actual irish melodies and polish music with what we would now call gospel but spiritual harmonies interlaced together with this african banjo
POD1000000017_S0000168	basically welding into a fusion that becomes the thing that everybody wants to try to do
POD1000000017_S0000170	the whole thing just sweeps the nation and for the rest of the nineteenth century this is the shit can we say that
POD1000000017_S0000172	and so for the rest of the nineteenth century this is the shit
POD1000000017_S0000174	this is america's primary form of entertainment people are going crazy for blackface minstrels you have little boys going to bed and dreaming about how they can become part of this minstrel show
POD1000000017_S0000175	some of those people having these dreams go on to become people like stephen foster
POD1000000017_S0000177	stephen foster the man widely credited as being the father of american music
POD1000000017_S0000179	some of his songs some of his most famous songs songs you know songs you love songs you still sing songs your children if you have them they still sing some of those songs were written for blackface performers
POD1000000017_S0000181	and if you listen to something like camptown races you can hear in it all of its minstrel properties
