YOU1000000002_S0000001	the wuhan coronavirus began like all new viruses with a remarkably ordinary moment
YOU1000000002_S0000002	in late november two thousand nineteen someone it is not yet known who ate a wild animal that by chance carried the novel coronavirus
YOU1000000002_S0000003	and days later started to feel the symptoms of what initially seemed like a bad cold
YOU1000000002_S0000004	from there more individuals were infected at first through the consumption of other wild animals but later through direct human to human transmission
YOU1000000002_S0000005	for the entire month of december the virus was there in wuhan spreading but nobody knew it
YOU1000000002_S0000006	the cases presenting as pneumonia were at first considered to be caused by anyone of the countless other viruses that can create such symptoms
YOU1000000002_S0000007	eventually the escalation in cases and effect that almost all the first patients had bought food at one particular wild animal market caught the wuhan city government's attention
YOU1000000002_S0000008	the first official confirmation that something was up came on new year's eve
YOU1000000002_S0000009	december thirty first when the municipal health commission published a press release acknowledging the situation
YOU1000000002_S0000010	over a month after the first transmission at the time this was small local news
YOU1000000002_S0000011	only a few dozen cases of pneumonia in a city of millions in a country of a billion
YOU1000000002_S0000012	but then came the news that this was not one of the many pre-existing pneumonia causing viruses
YOU1000000002_S0000013	this was something new western media first reported on the novel coronavirus around january eighth
YOU1000000002_S0000014	the new york times forebodingly wrote there is no evidence that the new virus is readily spread by humans and it has not been tied to any deaths
YOU1000000002_S0000015	that would soon change
YOU1000000002_S0000016	on january twenty first when the world health organization started tracking the outbreak there were two hundred and eighty two cases
YOU1000000002_S0000017	the next day three hundred and fourteen the next five hundred and eighty one
YOU1000000002_S0000018	then eight hundred and forty six then one thousand three hundred and twenty
YOU1000000002_S0000019	then two thousand and fourteen and by the start of the week of january twenty sixth it was clear that this would not be a quick and painless virus
YOU1000000002_S0000020	this would be one for the history books and it was going to get a lot worse before it got any better
YOU1000000002_S0000021	drastic circumstances called for drastic action it was clear given the trends that wuhan's hospitals would soon be overwhelmed by patients
YOU1000000002_S0000022	and in the case of highly infectious viruses like coronavirus that makes a bad situation worse as infected individuals will try to recover at home
YOU1000000002_S0000023	where the virus can more easily spread therefore the decision was made on january twenty-third to build a brand new facility capable of treating one thousand patients at once
YOU1000000002_S0000024	huoshenshan hospital it was announced that this would be done fully constructed by february second
YOU1000000002_S0000025	just ten days later
YOU1000000002_S0000026	china has experienced with such a feat in two thousand three the country suffered an outbreak of severe acute respiratory syndrome or sars which is also caused by a form of coronavirus
YOU1000000002_S0000027	much like with the novel coronavirus hospitals were overwhelmed and many had to turn away patients
YOU1000000002_S0000028	in response the government decided to build a new hospital
YOU1000000002_S0000029	over six days seven thousand construction workers brought the xiaotangshan hospital into reality and it quickly began accepting patients and relieving the overstressed medical system
YOU1000000002_S0000030	once the outbreak settled down the xiaotangshan hospital was hailed as a massive success by both the country itself and the world health organization
YOU1000000002_S0000031	the statistics speak for themselves overall sars had a fatality rate of nine point six percent
YOU1000000002_S0000032	at the xiaotangshan hospital just one point two percent of patients died
YOU1000000002_S0000033	and not a single staff member was infected
YOU1000000002_S0000034	it's no wonder why china wanted to replicate this
YOU1000000002_S0000035	and therefore xiaotangshan was the model for the new coronavirus hospital but this time would be different
YOU1000000002_S0000036	the two thousand three hospital began construction over six months after the beginning of the outbreak
YOU1000000002_S0000037	the two thousand and twenty hospital started construction less than two months after the first case and just days after the seriousness of the outbreak became clear
YOU1000000002_S0000038	there was far less time for planning and design the orders came and then it was immediately time to start
YOU1000000002_S0000039	step one was finding a place to put the hospital
YOU1000000002_S0000040	the location selected was previously just an open field about fourteen miles or twenty-two kilometers from central wuhan
YOU1000000002_S0000041	this kept it away from the dense urban core where further transmission might be easier but the field in question was also right off a large pre-existing road which made access easy
YOU1000000002_S0000042	that road was quickly shut down and turned into essentially a parking lot and staging area for the project
YOU1000000002_S0000043	the contract for this project was given to china construction third engineering bureau company a subsidiary of the state-owned china state construction engineering corporation
YOU1000000002_S0000044	by revenue this is the world's largest construction company and it has experience in enormous projects like beijing's new airport egypt's new capital city and tesla shanghai giga factory
YOU1000000002_S0000045	if anyone was going to pull this off it was them
YOU1000000002_S0000046	to begin construction in earnest they first needed to prepare the selected site
YOU1000000002_S0000047	that involved first cutting down all the trees and shrubbery and then perfectly levelling the ground
YOU1000000002_S0000048	out of the ten day construction timeline this took longer than one might think
YOU1000000002_S0000049	about forty-eight hours
YOU1000000002_S0000050	this was due in part to the fact that the project was significantly understaffed in its first few days
YOU1000000002_S0000051	as they scrambled to find workers especially as it's start coincided with the chinese new years
YOU1000000002_S0000052	once the land was level though they moved on to constructing the building foundations by sunday january twenty-sixth
YOU1000000002_S0000053	for this they used a layered system
YOU1000000002_S0000054	on the bottom at eight inch or twenty centimeter layer of sand was placed then what's referred to as a geotextile layer
YOU1000000002_S0000055	a formal fabric then a layer of waterproof plastic then another of geotextile layer then another layer of sand
YOU1000000002_S0000056	on that they then poured concrete which dried over a few days
YOU1000000002_S0000057	but then came the truly impressive element
YOU1000000002_S0000058	constructing the buildings themselves in a matter of days
YOU1000000002_S0000059	what made this possible was the use of pre-fabricated elements
YOU1000000002_S0000060	modular construction such as this has been on the rise recently
YOU1000000002_S0000061	it's now a well establish technique for the construction of buildings large and small
YOU1000000002_S0000062	the idea is simply that somewhere offsite in number of identical building elements are built
YOU1000000002_S0000063	then they're shipped to the construction site and put together
YOU1000000002_S0000064	this has plenty of advantages
YOU1000000002_S0000065	first and foremost the use of identical elements built in a factory system to construct a larger building lowers cost through economies of scale
YOU1000000002_S0000066	then when you actually get to putting the building together on site construction time is significantly less
YOU1000000002_S0000067	which once again lowers cost
YOU1000000002_S0000068	in this case though cost was not the primary concern
YOU1000000002_S0000069	speed was and modular construction is the fastest way to build
YOU1000000002_S0000070	most of these site used a type of prefabricated modular construction common with temporary buildings
YOU1000000002_S0000071	while it's not clear which company produce the prefabricated components it is clear that they existed before the project started
YOU1000000002_S0000072	the first building elements started coming together on monday january twenty-seventh just four days after the project broke grounds
YOU1000000002_S0000073	they began by building the skeleton on the modular units
YOU1000000002_S0000074	each of these units was about the shape and size of a twenty foot shipping container
YOU1000000002_S0000075	and this skeleton form included just the floor ceiling and structural supports at each corner
YOU1000000002_S0000076	throughout this all separate teams out of the thousands of workers there started to hook the site up to utilities like sewage water electricity and internet
YOU1000000002_S0000077	much of this just involved bringing in the state-owned companies responsible for these but for internet and the subsequent building out of an it system private companies like huawei and lenovo got involved
YOU1000000002_S0000078	this was no doubt partially because the construction of this hospital drew considerable public attention in china
YOU1000000002_S0000079	it came to represent the physical manifestation of the country's response to the crisis and also of china's engineering might
YOU1000000002_S0000080	the construction process itself was streamed by state-owned broadcasting companies and up to eighteen million concurrent viewers watched the process
YOU1000000002_S0000081	nearly every major broadcaster in china reporting from the site publishing footage like what you're seeing now although very few western broadcasters were there
YOU1000000002_S0000082	this is part of the reason limited detailed information and footage of the construction exists outside of china state-owned broadcasts
YOU1000000002_S0000083	where the government can manage the story and what gets out
YOU1000000002_S0000084	it was no doubt viewed as an opportunity by the chinese government in a time when they faced intense criticism for its initial response to the outbreak
YOU1000000002_S0000085	but of course to gain that praise the project needed to be successful
YOU1000000002_S0000086	on tuesday january twenty-eighth significant portions of the first building were completed while the rest of the complexes foundations were finishing up
YOU1000000002_S0000087	over the twenty-ninth and thirtieth more of the overall structure came to be as the walls were installed on and in the skeletons of buildings and work then began on turning these empty buildings into a hospital
YOU1000000002_S0000088	each patient room was outfitted with two beds some medical equipment and a bathroom
YOU1000000002_S0000089	considering the hospital is built with quarantine in mind there are some unique aspects to the design of these rooms
YOU1000000002_S0000090	for one the ventilation system is built to keep a negative pressure in all quarantine areas so that air will go out through an exhaust system rather than out under the door into the rest of the hospital
YOU1000000002_S0000091	while at the time of writing it's not entirely known to what extent this coronavirus can spread through airborne transmission a ventilation system like this is standard practice for any quarantine ward
YOU1000000002_S0000092	in addition to individual patient rooms separate areas were designed for patient processing diagnostic tools like c t scanners were installed and other crucial aspects like offices breakrooms and canteens were built in
YOU1000000002_S0000093	over the thirty-first of january and first and second of february the final areas of the complex were built up the interior installation was wrapped up and all the systems were tested to ensure that the hospital was ready to bring in patients
YOU1000000002_S0000094	meanwhile eight people's liberation army transport planes landed at wuhan airport carrying the military medical staff who would staff the hospital
YOU1000000002_S0000095	they moved into the facility throughout the same day february second then throughout the night workers put the finishing touches onto the hundreds of rooms
YOU1000000002_S0000096	then the next morning the moment that ten days prior seemed impossible arrived
YOU1000000002_S0000097	the first patients transferred from other facilities were wheeled into huoshenshan hospital and thus marked the beginning of its operations
YOU1000000002_S0000098	they started with just a few dozen patients but in a matter of days this ballooned to hundreds
YOU1000000002_S0000099	huoshenshan hospital was only the start of china's plan to ramp up the number of available beds in wuhan
YOU1000000002_S0000100	just three days after huoshenshan's opening another even larger hospital called leishenshan opened
YOU1000000002_S0000101	it's sixteen hundred beds and thirty-two wards were built in just twelve days
YOU1000000002_S0000102	meanwhile other hospitals were converted to isolate and treat coronavirus patients and stadiums and exhibition centers were turned into hospitals as well
YOU1000000002_S0000103	still though even with this swift decisive action reports indicate that many of those with milder cases of coronavirus are getting turned away from hospitals in wuhan
YOU1000000002_S0000104	it unfortunately seems that coronavirus with its tremendous severity is one of the few things that can outpace china
